pull_request.body:
This includes needing to migrate to a 'uv' based packaging system, since
that's what upstream did.

Unfortunately, `uv sync` as a FoD doesn't work since it's not a stable
output format.

I handled it by writing a hacky "uv.lock to nix" converter (in the form
of the 'update.sh' script), and then using fetchurl to download every
file referenced in the uv.lock.

Using that, combined with the "UV_FIND_LINKS" environment variable lets
uv operate offline, so it seems like that's a good enough solution
there, phew!

The next hurdle was that anki wants us to populate 'pyenv' for an
offline build, and I wasn't sure the exact right 'uv' commands for that.
I ended up with a mix of 'uv export' to make requirements.txt files, and
'uv pip install' to install em. That seems to work okay for most things.

The final problem was that using anki's suggested version of PyQt hits
linker errors. To me, the easiest solution seemed like just using the
already-packaged pyqt packages from nixpkgs, so I did that.

Overall, this feels pragmatic and like it works.

I think the most compelling alternative would be to generate
"requirements.txt" using uv export, relax all the version requirements,
and use nixpkgs-packaged dependencies only.
I ended up not taking that route because not all of anki's dependencies
are present in nixpkgs, and so doing it like done in this PR seemed more
expedient.

That's the notes I have, hopefully this approach seems overall
reasonable!

Fixes #422471

fix(crud): Correct column name in payment database queries

This commit fixes a typo in the column name used in the SQL queries
for `delete_wallet_payment` and `get_wallet_payment`. This was the
final blocker preventing the self-healing logic in the service layer
from working correctly.

The Bug:
The `delete_wallet_payment` function was attempting to execute a SQL
`DELETE` command using a `WHERE` clause with the column name `wallet`.
However, the actual column name in the `apipayments` table is
`wallet_id`.

This caused the function to crash with an `UndefinedColumnError` every
time it was called, as correctly pointed out by the database error logs.

The Fix:
The column name in the SQL query within `delete_wallet_payment` has
been corrected from `wallet` to `wallet_id`, and the corresponding
parameter in the values dictionary has been updated to match.

As a proactive measure, the same latent typo was found and corrected in
the `get_wallet_payment` function.

Why It's Safe:
This is a low-risk and necessary correction. It does not alter any
business logic. It simply aligns the database access code with the
actual database schema, fixing a clear and verifiable typo. This change
is essential, as it unblocks the self-healing mechanism in the service
layer, allowing it to properly delete the corrupted duplicate payment
records that were causing the chain of errors.
